          "body": "Ezra 6 opens in the administrative machinery of the Persian Empire. Darius orders a search — not of Judah's records, not of the temple ruins, but of the imperial archives in Babylon. The search turns up nothing there. The decisive scroll is found instead in the fortress at Ecbatana in Media (6:2), the summer capital of Cyrus himself. That a building decree issued twenty-two years earlier, filed in a remote Median fortress, survived intact and was retrievable on demand is not presented as administrative efficiency — it is the narrator's first signal that a hand beyond Darius's is at work. The content of the scroll (vv. 3-5) is striking in its specificity: dimensions, materials, funding source, and — crucially — the mandate to return the temple utensils Nebuchadnezzar had plundered. The same items looted by Babylon's king are now legally required to be restored by Persia's king. What one empire stole, a successor empire is commanded to return. The arc of history bends not toward imperial continuity but toward the God whose house stands in Jerusalem."
