          "body": "The chapter's final movement is its most theologically resonant. One month after the temple's completion, the restored community observes the Passover (6:19) — the feast that commemorates the first Exodus from Egypt. The choice to conclude the temple-completion narrative with Passover is not accidental; it is the narrator's interpretive key. The return from Babylonian exile is being read through the template of the Exodus. The community has been brought out of a second Egypt, through a second wilderness, into a land that still requires cleansing and ordered worship. The Passover table is extended to 'all those who had separated themselves from the impurity of the nations of the land to join them, to seek the LORD God of Israel' (6:21). The boundary of the covenant community is drawn not by ethnicity but by covenant allegiance — a principle that will generate the crisis of chapters 9-10 when the reverse becomes true (covenant people assimilating into nations' impurity). The chapter closes with the LORD as its subject: He 'caused them to rejoice,' and He 'turned the heart of the king of Assyria toward them to encourage them in the work' (6:22). The 'king of Assyria' — an archaic title applied to the Persian king as heir of the Neo-Assyrian empire — has had his heart turned by the same God who turned Pharaoh's heart and hardened it in the original Exodus narrative. Here the sovereign who moves kings moves them toward Israel's blessing rather than their oppression. The chapter, and the first half of Ezra, ends with joy — God-given, temple-centered, covenant-feast-shaped joy."
